{
  "answer": "**Bṛhaspati Smṛti (Chapter 1, section 1.5 on Witnesses)** enumerates twelve kinds of witnesses: a subscribed witness, a recorded witness, a *concealed witness* (gūḍha), a reminded witness, a kinsman, a messenger, a chance witness, a secondary witness, one present at the transaction, a king, a chief judge, and the village.[^1]\n\nThe concealed witness (*gūḍha sākṣin*) is defined as follows: \"He who, concealed by a wall, is made to hear a statement about a debt, and who, when it is denied, relates it as it happened, is called a concealed witness.\" // Brh_1,5.8 //[^2]\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-0cc2ab).\n\n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-2ee353).",
